,Recommended,321870,12444497,"Posted: 10 October, 2014",all,Casta,"Please... Forgive me.These are the opening words of the protagonist (or unorthodox anti-hero) Jacob B. Reeves as he stands in front of the choice whether to plummet into the abyss beneath or not, with the choice already chosen for you.Graphics/art style - 10/10During that short scene and every subsequent scene thereafter, you'll notice a unique style to the game, artisticly for one, that immediatly catches your eye. Jacob has a face when dialog is presented, but at all other times, he is a pitch black silhouette shape of a man, which begs for interpretation throughout the entire game. Beatifully crafted envoirnments and characters (monsters, eeeeh) separates this game from alot of others titles flooding the marked.Gameplay - 8/10Moving through the, presumably, personal hell of Jacobs own making, alot of things are thrown at you and sometimes, mostly, thinking on your feet (fingers?) will get you through it. Some things take trial and error until you go ""Aaaah, DOH!"" and then there's the frustration inducing ""DOH! AAAARH!""Then there are some puzzles/actions required, that gives no explanation when it is most needed. The first 4-5 instructions are short, informative and precise but it kind of falters after that. Spending 20 minutes rotating a bobby pin lockpick, having no clue what cues to go after, walking around a cottage for just below 1 hour confused because I decided to take a break, return to the game and having NO idea what to do, so a little (Hate myself for suggesting it) 'objective' reminder would have been alot of help and basic instructions in some places.Soundtrack 7/10I love a good soundtrack, but trying to remember some of the music, I honestly draw a blank. I remember thinking ""Stellar soundtrack!"" during different points of the game, but games like Bastion, Hotline Miami, Super Meat Boy are lightyears ahead of tailoring music to the game, but that is okay! Making a memorable OST would be a nightmare for the general person, me especially, because where would you start?! So considering what limitations there is, the OST for Silence of the Sleep is good as it is experienced ingame.Overall - 9/10Jesse Makonnen -the games creator- and all who helped him out in his 1½ year stretch to finish this game did a FANTASTIC job! With an ending that draws from suprising parts of your journey, to disturbing SUDDEN moments that make you wretch, this is a game every fan of a good story and horror should not miss, especially with a 15$ / 15€ pricetag for hours of gameplay, despite a few pacing problems!SITENOTE---The game bugged out in chapter 3, where it is suppose to initiate a cutscene. After specific dialog happens, you are put outside the room you were in without warning; deceptivly unlucky that is does so without hiccups, so when you were about to progress it brainfarted maximum and had me walking around for 2 hours before resetting and moving on ingame, just a heads up---"
