,Recommended,321870,12547967,"Posted: 18 October, 2014",all,Glycerin Ghost,"An intruiging story that only continues to pull you into the madness of the mind. As you click New Game, the man backs himself over the cliff's edge and the story begins.A sidescroller that uses silhouettes, you are in the shoes of a man who knows not where he is or even who he is. He meets a mysterious bartender who holds his answers and his journey to self discovery begins. Avoiding disturbing shadows and solving clever puzzles, jumping at the random bumps and sounds, I found myself engrossed in the story as each chapter presents another side of the world, while the protangonist digs deeper to find out why he is here in this place.As the story continues (trying not to spoil anything), you discover that not everyone wants to leave, not everyone wants to know how they got here. Some are too afraid and others have their minds on other things. You press on and find that there is a price to this journey. The bartender himself tells you that 'Your journey will be riddled with terror and it's not an easy one to take. But you have the choice to stay or press on.'If you enjoy atmospheric horror, buy this.If you like an engrossing story with twists, buy this.I can not praise this game enough, and anymore might spoil some things. But I HIGHLY recommend it. I beat it in about 6 hours, got stuck at some really clever puzzles, but the time was well spent. At one point, I found myself dying to know what would happen next. I hope you enjoy this as much as I did."
76561197978893994,Recommended,321870,20242352,"Posted: 2 January, 2016",all,agentdiner,"A haunting, visceral and occasionally frustrating journey through a shattered psyche, Silence of the Sleep is set in a stunningly realised vision of a mind coming to grips with pain, loss and grief, as well as the tormented and fractured path to realisation after personal tragedy.Set against a dark, brooding art style and a despairing rain washed sky, a man plunges from a clifftop, asking for forgiveness. From here a strange, surreal journey through his past actions and memories plays out in a side scrolling, slow paced and intensely unnerving narrative, involving puzzle elements and avoidance combat with enemies. The man, Jacob, finds himself in one strange place after another, always somehow familiar and oddly out of place. The people he meets are cryptic and often vague about what they are doing there or how indeed they got there, and no one really seems to know what's going on.One of the game's biggest strengths is its sense of foreboding atmosphere. Each location feels disconnected from any proper sense of reality, and the player is constantly uneasy about what could be around the next corner or hiding in the shadows. This is largely due to the incredible atmosphere the game creates through a minimilistic and strikingly unique art style and colour tone, with oppresively dark, dirty environments contrasted against gashes of bright red of blood soaked interiors. The visuals, as the essence of the world, perfectly encapture a broken, twisted and depressing place that allows the theme of the story to shine through brightly in this dark nightmare.The sound direction and design is some of the best I've witnessed in any game. Ambient creaks and gnarls of the environment echo around the player as they navigate through the game's locations, always keeping tension just tangible enough to keep the player's wariness at a draining level. The shrills and alien cries of the grotesque, deforrmed monsters instill such dread that for the most part their presence is a terrifying and heart pounding thrill. There is a beautiful musical score throughout the journey, across many instruments and often involving the player's input. The overture haunts and bleeds as the story unravels, and fills the sky of the game like the grey, oozing rain that never stops.Gameplay revolves primarily around exploring areas, finding items or clues to advance to the next area, talking to NPC's and avoiding the enemy monsters. There is no combat at all, and if you get too close to the enemies its Game Over. This allows for a tense hide and seek between you and the patrolling enemies as you navigate the dark hallways and hide to avoid a quick death. While this system is effective and can be genuinely skin crawling, it can get incredibly frustrating when you are trying to solve puzzles or get through an area and have to constantly stop and wait for the enemies to pass. In fact, this might be the biggest gripe I have with the game and I spent a lot of time reloading again and again with growing annoyance at some sections, as a simple task could stretch well beyond the point of tension or enjoyment.The puzzles are fairly straightforward but fit in well with the world created. The story unravels slowly and deliberatley vaguely, never completely telling the player everything and shrouding the whole experience in a veil of uncertainty and clouded clarity. The story's tone and somewhat ambiguous nature is perfectly presented in the dark, dank and gloomy environments, and the twisted and sporadic nature of the events that occur. Jacob can rarely discern what is real or indeed what is happening, and the player is just as submerged in this confusion. The player wanders the levels in the crushing darkness, getting lost and fumbling through rooms hoping to find the next clue, just as they do with the game's narrative.Overall, Silence of the Sleep is a beautiful, terrifying experience, not so much for the scares it imbues but more toward the brutal tone and theme of Jacob's journey. Life and death is presented as shards of glass, constantly sticking and twisting into the strange world as Jacob's memories and emotions bleed onto the screen. It's not perfect and will most likely frustrate, but as a grim walk down a very mature and despondent road, it is a marvellous, dreadful time."
